arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
August 10, 2001

Area F

Trench 7

Katie Smith

Today we began by cleaning the entire trench and taking opening elevations. After this was accomplished there was a no-holds-barred on the trench and we worked on the entire area of the 10x10.

Some of the workmen began by taking down the elevation in the northwestern quarter of the trench by 10-15 cms. In doing so, we leveled the pit L7021 and closed it today. We also uncovered another cobbled surface. It occurs in the northeastern-most corner of L7019 and probably extends eastward into L7020. We started taking the elevation down in L7020 so we could continue troweling but did not finish before the end of the day. We assigned the new surface as L7029.

In the northeast corner of the trench, Amy continued articulating and extracting burial L7006. I wanted to make a quick note about elevations. L7013 is the fill around burial L7006. When we take elevations it is on the dirt surrounding the head and foot of the skeleton, so that is why the elevations for both loci are identical on the KT sheet.

There were a few workmen concentrating on L7014 and trying to follow the cobbled surrounding the conglomerate of rocks, pebbles, and sand. We extended it Eastward (we peeled back a portion of L7020 in doing so) and we will try and follow the surface northward and westward tomorrow. Another elevation note: the high elevation in this locus is the rock on the conglomerate hump that will not change until we are finished with the locus and whack it. So, that would explain the constant high elevation of 66.37.

The last day we excavated (8/5/1) we had found another cranium in L7020 and had not opened a new locus for it due to time constraints. Today we did open it as burial L7028. The cranium is in the middle of a 1x1 meter area for further articulation/extraction.

The last area we worked on was L7026. We removed all of the pottery and finally found the associated surface. We closed pottery debris layer/fill L7026 and opened surface L7030. We also continued to take down the elevation in L7015 in hopes to connect surfaces L7010 and L7030, but so far to no avail. We will continue tomorrow.

(AS) Today we finished exposing the skeleton and began excavating it. The skull was in bad shape and several broken pieces came off before we had it wrapped in tin foil. Also, we dug a little around the distal ends of the legs to look for foot bones before taking out more of the bulk and didn't find any so we left the baulk there.

  Several of the bones have a yellowish-orange color to them, resembling the color of clay. Some of the bones seem to be stuck together very tightly and it may be difficult to separate them without breaking them.
